      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do you mean by \"goblin of debt\"? i just wanted to understand the math part. can you just explain the math without the metaphors?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the math.\n\nThe interest calculation on a declining balance loan is based on the outstanding balance. The formula for calculating the interest is:\n\nInterest = Outstanding Balance x Interest Rate x Time Period\n\nIn the case of a monthly payment, the time period is usually a month. The outstanding balance is reduced by the payment amount each month, and the interest is calculated on the new balance.\n\nFor example, if your loan balance is $10,000, the interest rate is 6%, and you make a $100 payment each month, the interest calculation would be:\n\nMonth 1:\nInterest = $10,000 x 0.06 x 1 = $600\nBalance after payment = $10,000 - $100 = $9,900\nInterest for Month 2 = $9,900 x 0.06 x 1 = $594\nBalance after payment = $9,900 - $100 = $9,800\n\nAnd so on. The interest is calculated on the outstanding balance each month, and the balance is reduced by the payment amount.\n\nAs for the \"goblin of debt\", I was just trying to make a point about how the",
      "source": "target",
